==Kähler manifolds==
On a Kähler manifold formula_5, the Ricci curvature determines the 
curvature form of the canonical line bundle 
. The canonical line bundle is the top 
exterior power of the bundle of holomorphic Kähler differentials:

formula_165

The Levi-Civita connection corresponding to the metric on formula_5 gives 
rise to a connection on formula_167. The curvature of this connection is 
the 2-form defined by 

formula_168

where formula_169 is the complex structure map on the 
tangent bundle determined by the structure of the Kähler manifold. The Ricci 
form is a closed 2-form. Its cohomology class is, 
up to a real constant factor, the first Chern class of the canonical bundle, 
and is therefore a topological invariant of formula_5 (for compact formula_5) 
in the sense that it depends only on the topology of formula_5 and the 
homotopy class of the complex structure.

Conversely, the Ricci form determines the Ricci tensor by

formula_173

In local holomorphic coordinates formula_174, the Ricci form is given by

formula_175

where is the Dolbeault operator and

formula_176

If the Ricci tensor vanishes, then the canonical bundle is flat, so the 
structure group can be locally reduced to a subgroup of the 
special linear group formula_177. However, Kähler manifolds 
already possess holonomy in formula_178, and so the (restricted) 
holonomy of a Ricci-flat Kähler manifold is contained in formula_179. 
Conversely, if the (restricted) holonomy of a 2formula_2-dimensional Riemannian 
manifold is contained in formula_179, then the manifold is a Ricci-flat 
Kähler manifold .

==Generalization to affine connections==
The Ricci tensor can also be generalized to arbitrary affine connections, 
where it is an invariant that plays an especially important role in the study of 
projective geometry (geometry associated to 
unparameterized geodesics) . If formula_3 
denotes an affine connection, then the curvature tensor formula_10 is the 
(1,3)-tensor defined by

formula_184

for any vector fields formula_9. The Ricci tensor is defined to be the trace:

formula_186

In this more general situation, the Ricci tensor is symmetric if and only if there 
exists locally a parallel volume form for the connection.

== Discrete Ricci curvature ==
Notions of Ricci curvature on discrete manifolds have been defined on graphs and
networks, where they quantify local divergence properties of edges. Ollivier&#x27;s 
Ricci curvature is defined using optimal transport theory. 
A different (and earlier) notion, Forman&#x27;s Ricci curvature, is based on 
topological arguments.

